{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17411383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17411383"},"attributes":{"position":5,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13988"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476898"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13988"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260986"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T06:24:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:02:58+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":13,"questionsAnswered":0,"marksTotal":0,"marksAttainable":0,"marksAttempted":0,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T06:25:33+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"13988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13988"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.84,0.03,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6622"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49015"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6622"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13988"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34033"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1224"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"8183"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32841"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44190"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49015"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with a two-week history of worsening eczema. He has patches of dry, red, and itchy skin on his arms, legs, and torso. His parent reports bathing him twice daily with soap to keep him clean, thinking this would help the eczema. The boy has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His skin is dry with erythematous patches and excoriations consistent with eczema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Refer to a dermatologist","Advise once-daily bathing with emollient application","Advise to avoid bathing for one week","Prescribe a potent topical corticosteroid","Recommend continuing twice-daily baths with soap"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial step in managing this child\u0027s eczema is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadvise once-daily bathing with emollient application\u003C/strong\u003E. The parent\u0027s current practice of bathing the child twice daily with soap is likely exacerbating the eczema by drying out the skin and disrupting its natural barrier function. Reducing bath frequency and applying emollients immediately after bathing are key components of eczema management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing a potent topical corticosteroid\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the most appropriate first step. While topical corticosteroids are often used in eczema management, they should be reserved for flare-ups and used judiciously, especially in children. The initial focus should be on improving skincare practices.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommending continuing twice-daily baths with soap\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this practice is likely contributing to the worsening of the eczema. Soap can strip the skin of its natural oils, leading to dryness and irritation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvising to avoid bathing for one week\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary and may lead to poor hygiene. Instead, the focus should be on proper bathing techniques that don\u0027t exacerbate eczema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring to a dermatologist\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary if the eczema doesn\u0027t improve with primary care management, but it\u0027s not the most appropriate initial step. General practitioners can effectively manage most cases of childhood eczema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct approach involves educating the parent about proper skincare for eczema. This includes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReducing bath frequency to once daily or every other day\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUsing lukewarm water and avoiding hot water\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUsing a mild, fragrance-free cleanser instead of soap\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELimiting bath time to 5-10 minutes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatting the skin dry gently after bathing\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApplying an emollient liberally within 3 minutes of bathing to lock in moisture\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmollients are the cornerstone of eczema management and should be applied multiple times daily. By improving skincare practices and moisturising appropriately, many cases of eczema can be significantly improved without the need for additional interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Frequent bathing and use of soap can exacerbate eczema by drying out the skin.","Emollients are the cornerstone of eczema management and should be applied liberally and frequently.","Patient and parent education is crucial in the successful management of childhood eczema."],"references":["Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Eczema clinical practice guidelines. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/eczema/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34033"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13988"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34033"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-22T14:30:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-04T14:35:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6622"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49015"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-